 for bestpractices and # Two-Factor Authentication (2FA)

## Overview
Implement optional Two-Factor Authentication (2FA) for Archject accounts to improve security for sensitive accounts and enterprise customers. Provide both TOTP (authenticator apps) and SMS OTP (via Twilio) with flows to enable/disable 2FA, verify codes at login and for sensitive actions, issue recovery codes, and provide rate limiting and anti-brute-force protections. Integrate 2FA controls into the User Profile page and surface checks on the Login/Signup page. Allow enterprise admins to require 2FA for workspace members via a tenant setting.

## Components to Build
- 2FA Backend Service
  - TOTP generation and verification (RFC6238)
  - SMS OTP send & verify using Twilio (with templated messages, configurable sender)
  - Recovery code generation, storage (hashed), and one-time use logic
  - Rate limiting, attempt counters, exponential backoff and lockouts
  - Audit logs for enable/disable, failed/successful verifies, recovery code use
- API Endpoints
  - Enable/Disable 2FA (TOTP or SMS)
  - Generate TOTP secret & QR payload
  - Verify 2FA code (for enable flow and login flows)
  - Send SMS OTP (for enable flow and login flows)
  - Validate SMS delivery & Twilio webhook handling (optional)
  - Endpoint to generate and display recovery codes (download/print)
  - Admin endpoints to require 2FA at tenant level
- Frontend
  - User Profile 2FA management UI (enable/disable, switch method, regen recovery codes, show status)
  - Login/Signup page integration: prompt for 2FA when required or configured, option to use authenticator or SMS, enter recovery code
  - TOTP setup modal with QR code and copyable secret; instructions and verification step
  - SMS phone number entry/verification flow with resend and countdown
  - Error states, lockout messages, and guidance for lost device/recovery codes
- Twilio Integration
  - Configurable provider keys in environment / admin console
  - SMS send logic with templated OTP and rate limits
  - Optional Twilio webhook endpoint for delivery receipts (for monitoring)
- Security
  - Hash storage for recovery codes using bcrypt/Argon2
  - Store TOTP secrets encrypted at rest (application-level KMS or encryption key)
  - Short-lived OTP tokens and strict verification windows
  - Logging and monitoring for suspicious patterns
- Tests
  - Unit tests for TOTP algorithm, SMS flows (mock Twilio), recovery code logic
  - Integration tests for API endpoints and login flows
  - Security tests for brute-force protections and lockouts

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
Pages & Components:
- User Profile Page (page_profile)
  - 2FA Card (card-style per design system):
    - Status line: "2FA: Disabled / Enabled (TOTP / SMS)"
    - Primary actions:
      - Enable 2FA (opens modal with selection: Authenticator App or SMS)
      - Disable 2FA (confirmation modal + require current password + 2FA code if enabled)
      - Regenerate Recovery Codes (modal with copy/download)
      - Change phone number (if SMS selected)
    - Secondary: Short help text describing recovery options and enterprise enforcement.
  - TOTP Setup Modal:
    - Title, short instructions
    - QR code image (data URI) displayed inside a white card with subtle shadow
    - Copy secret button (with tooltip) and copy-to-clipboard microinteraction
    - Input field to verify 6-digit code (numeric-only, spaced grouping optional)
    - Submit button (primary #0052CC)
    - Alternate option: "Use SMS instead"
  - SMS Setup Modal:
    - Phone number input with international formatting (E.164) and validation
    - Send OTP button (disabled when countdown active)
    - OTP input and verify button
    - Resend link visible after configurable cooldown; show resend countdown
    - Info about carrier message rates and opt-out
  - Recovery Codes Modal:
    - Show list of 8-12 single-use codes in a grid; copy / download as .txt button
    - Warning: "Store these in a safe place. Each can be used once."
- Login / Signup Page (page_login_signup)
  - Unified auth form supports:
    - Email + password sign-in
    - SSO / OAuth buttons (unchanged)
    - Link to Sign Up and Password Reset
  - After successful primary auth (password or SSO), if user has 2FA:
    - Present 2FA step overlay or inline form:
      - Method label (Authenticator app or SMS to +X)
      - Numeric code input (6 digits) with submit
      - Link "Use a recovery code" toggling to recovery code input
      - For SMS method: "Send code" button (resend cooldown)
      - Option "Remember this device" checkbox (persisted with secure cookie or device token; optional expiry)
  - Error and lockout states:
    - Show clear messages on invalid code, remaining attempts, temporary lockout, and links to support
  - UX microcopy and accessible labels per design system

Accessibility & UI Behavior:
- Inputs labeled and accessible via keyboard/screen reader
- QR image has alt text and fallback showable secret
- Color usage per palette; error status uses #EF4444, success #10B981
- Use cards, spacing, and typography per design system

State & Client Storage:
- "Remember this device" should create a signed device-token cookie with short TTL (e.g., 30 days) and stored server-side mapping (device id → user id, created, expires)
- Never store TOTP secrets or full recovery codes in client storage beyond ephemeral copy clipboard

### Backend
Core services and functions:
- TOTP Service
  - Use standard library (e.g., otplib, speakeasy) to generate secrets, QR URIs (otpauth://) and verify codes with ±1 time-step skew
  - Store the TOTP secret encrypted in DB (AES-256 with server-side key or KMS)
- SMS OTP Service
  - Generate secure, random numeric OTPs (6 digits), store hashed OTP with expiry (e.g., 5–10 minutes)
  - Send via Twilio Programmable SMS; template: "Archject verification code: 123456 — Expires in 10 minutes."
  - Prevent resend floods with per-phone and per-user cooldowns and max sends per hour
- Recovery Codes
  - Generate 8-12 random tokens (10+ chars), store only hashed versions (bcrypt/Argon2), mark used when consumed
  - Provide one-time display after generation (require user to copy/download)
- APIs
  - Robust API endpoints (details below)
  - Rate-limit endpoints related to OTP/verify per IP and per user
  - Login flow should support an intermediate state: a session or temporary token indicating primary auth passed but 2FA required
  - Sessions/cookies: Only create full session after 2FA verified (unless device remembered)
- Tenant (workspace) Setting
  - Admin API to set "Require 2FA for all members" boolean flag
  - Enforce at authentication and membership change points
- Audit & Logging
  - Store events: 2fa.enabled, 2fa.disabled, 2fa.verified, 2fa.failed, recovery.used
  - Include actor, IP, user-agent, timestamp, and tenant id
- Twilio Integration
  - Config via environment variables and admin UI for provisioning keys
  - Optional webhook endpoint to receive message status updates; update OTP delivery status logs
- Security controls
  - Enforce OTP attempt limits (e.g., 5 attempts per code), lock account 15 minutes after repeated failures
  - Lockouts should be per user and per IP with exponential backoff
  - Ensure replay protection for OTPs and recovery codes
  - Use CSRF protections on enable/disable endpoints
- Tests and Mocks
  - Mock Twilio in test and staging environments (record and replay)
  - Unit tests for encrypted storage and recovery code checks

### Integration
- Login flow:
  - After primary credential validation, backend returns 2FA_required response if enabled (status 206 or specific JSON field). Client shows 2FA step and sends verify to /auth/2fa/verify.
  - On successful 2FA verification, backend issues full session cookie or token.
- Device remember:
  - If user checks "Remember this device", backend issues device token cookie and stores device fingerprint with expiry, so subsequent logins from that device skip 2FA.
- Profile:
  - Profile page uses authenticated API to fetch 2FA status and available actions.
- Twilio:
  - SMS send calls to Twilio happen server-side only; verify Twilio errors and surfacing to user.
  - Optionally, Twilio webhooks update delivery logs to help troubleshooting message failures.

## User Experience Flow

1. Enable 2FA (TOTP)
   - User opens Profile → 2FA card → clicks Enable → chooses "Authenticator app".
   - Backend creates TOTP secret, stores encrypted; returns otpauth URI and raw secret to frontend.
   - Frontend displays TOTP Setup Modal: QR code + secret. User scans with app.
   - User enters 6-digit code and clicks Verify.
   - Backend verifies code; on success: mark 2FA enabled (method = TOTP), generate recovery codes (show once), and show success toast.
   - On failure: show error, allow retry; enforce attempt rate-limits.

2. Enable 2FA (SMS)
   - User chooses "SMS" in enable flow; enters phone number; clicks Send OTP.
   - Backend validates phone, generates OTP, sends via Twilio, persist hashed OTP + expiry.
   - Frontend shows OTP input, with resend cooldown and attempts remaining.
   - On verify: mark 2FA enabled (method = SMS), generate recovery codes, show success.

3. Login with 2FA
   - User enters credentials; backend authenticates password and detects 2FA.
   - Backend responds that 2FA is required; frontend shows 2FA step with method hint.
   - For TOTP: user enters code; for SMS: user clicks "Send code" to receive SMS then enters code.
   - Option to use recovery code if necessary.
   - On success: create session token, redirect to app.
   - On repeated failures: show clear lockout messages and support options.

4. Disable 2FA
   - User clicks Disable on Profile 2FA card; must enter current password and a valid 2FA code (or recovery code) to confirm.
   - Backend verifies both and sets 2fa.enabled = false, deletes TOTP secret and recovery codes, logs event.

5. Lost Device / Recovery Codes
   - If user lost device, they may use a recovery code at 2FA prompt.
   - If recovery codes are exhausted, admin or support can trigger account-level resets after verification. Admin flow must require strict identity checks and audit logging.

6. Enterprise Enforcement
   - Workspace admin toggles "Require 2FA" in settings.
   - After toggling on, unattested users receive an email/in-app notice prompting 2FA setup; existing logins require enabling 2FA on next login or block access until enabled (configurable grace period).

## Technical Specifications

- Data Models:
  - users (existing) — extend:
    - 2fa_enabled: boolean
    - 2fa_method: enum('totp', 'sms', null)
    - 2fa_secret_enc: string (encrypted)
    - phone_number: string (E.164) [if SMS]
    - 2fa_recovery_generated_at: datetime
  - recovery_codes
    - id
    - user_id (FK)
    - code_hash (string)
    - used_at (nullable datetime)
  - sms_otps
    - id
    - user_id (nullable) — for pre-enablement or login flows
    - phone_number
    - otp_hash
    - expires_at
    - attempts_remaining (int)
    - created_at
    - status (pending/sent/failed)
  - device_tokens
    - id
    - user_id
    - device_name
    - token_hash
    - created_at
    - expires_at
    - last_used_at
  - audit_events
    - id, user_id, actor_id, tenant_id, event_type, meta(json), ip, ua, created_at
  - tenant_settings
    - tenant_id, require_2fa boolean, require_2fa_grace_period_days int

- API Endpoints:
  - POST /api/auth/login
    - body: {email, password, remember_me}
    - response: {2fa_required: bool, 2fa_methods: [ 'totp' | 'sms' ], phone_masked }
  - POST /api/auth/2fa/send-sms
    - body: {user_id or session_temp_token, phone_number, purpose: 'enable'|'login'}
    - response: {sent: true, cooldown_seconds}
  - POST /api/auth/2fa/verify
    - body: {session_temp_token, code, method: 'totp'|'sms'|'recovery', remember_device: bool}
    - response: {authenticated: true, session_token or cookie}
  - POST /api/auth/2fa/totp/setup
    - auth required
    - response: {otpauth_uri, secret, qr_data_uri}
  - POST /api/auth/2fa/enable
    - body: {method, verification_code, phone_number (if sms)}
    - auth required; confirm password
    - response: {enabled: true, recovery_codes: [plain_codes]}
  - POST /api/auth/2fa/disable
    - body: {password, code}
    - auth required
  - GET /api/user/2fa/status
    - returns 2fa status, method, phone masked, last_enforced_by_admin flag
  - POST /api/user/2fa/recovery/regenerate
    - auth required; confirm password and 2FA; returns new codes
  - POST /api/admin/tenant/2fa
    - body: {tenant_id, require_2fa, grace_days}
  - Webhook: POST /api/integrations/twilio/webhook (optional)
- Security:
  - Authentication:
    - Primary credentials validated first; only issue final session after 2FA unless device remembered
    - Use secure, HttpOnly, SameSite=Lax/Strict cookies for session tokens
  - Authorization:
    - Only authenticated users may manage their 2FA settings; tenant admins modify tenant-level settings
    - Admin-only endpoints protected by RBAC
  - Secrets & Storage:
    - TOTP secrets encrypted server-side using a key stored in KMS or environment vault; keys rotated per policy
    - Recovery codes stored hashed (bcrypt/Argon2)
    - OTP and device tokens stored hashed
  - Rate limiting & brute-force:
    - /auth/2fa/verify: max 5 attempts per code, per user; then block for 15 minutes; escalate per IP if abnormal
    - /auth/2fa/send-sms: max 3 sends per 10 minutes per phone and per user
    - Global per-IP request throttling for auth endpoints
  - Logging & monitoring for suspicious activity and alerting for high failure rates
  - CSRF protection on state-changing endpoints
  - Input sanitization and strict validation

- Validation:
  - Phone numbers: validate and normalize to E.164; use libphonenumber
  - OTP codes: numeric-only length 6 for TOTP/SMS; recovery codes pattern for expected length
  - Password confirmation required for enable/disable/regenerate recovery codes
  - Enforce unique phone per user constraint only if desired; otherwise allow duplicate numbers with tenant policy
  - Reject enabling SMS with disposable/voip numbers (optional check via 3rd-party service)

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] A user can enable 2FA via authenticator app: QR and secret appear; verification code must validate; recovery codes generated and displayed exactly once.
- [ ] A user can enable 2FA via SMS: valid E.164 phone entry, Twilio sends OTP, code verifies, and 2FA switches to SMS.
- [ ] On login, users with 2FA enabled are required to complete 2FA before obtaining a full session; both TOTP and SMS flows work end-to-end.
- [ ] Recovery codes work once each; used codes are marked and cannot be reused.
- [ ] Disabling 2FA requires password + 2FA (or recovery code) verification; logs an audit event.
- [ ] Rate limiting and lockout prevent brute-force: >5 failed attempts triggers temporary lockout and appropriate user-facing message.
- [ ] Tenant admin can enable "Require 2FA" for workspace; users are prompted on next login and access is blocked after grace period if not enabled.
- [ ] Twilio integration sends SMS in staging/dev via mock and in production with real provider; failures are handled gracefully and surfaced to user.
- [ ] All sensitive secrets (TOTP secret, recovery codes) stored encrypted/hashed and never exposed after initial display.
- [ ] Frontend components match the provided Visual Style and accessibility guidelines.

## UI/UX Guidelines
Apply the project's design system:
- Use the provided color palette; primary action buttons use #0052CC, errors use #EF4444, success #10B981.
- Card-based layout for 2FA sections; white cards (#FFFFFF) with subtle shadow and 8–12px radius.
- Headings follow hierarchy (H2 ~22px for section titles).
- Inputs rounded with #D1D5DB borders, clear focus ring, and accessible labels.
- Buttons: primary solid (#0052CC), secondary ghost/outline.
- Microcopy:
  - TOTP setup: "Scan this QR code with your authenticator app (e.g., Google Authenticator, Authy). Enter the 6-digit code to confirm."
  - SMS setup: "Standard message rates may apply. If you do not receive a code within 2 minutes try resending."
  - Recovery codes: "Store these codes safely. Each code can be used once to sign in if you lose access to your 2FA device."
- Navigation: Keep 2FA controls prominently in Profile page under "Security" card, with consistent spacing and left-aligned labels.

Design elements specifics:
- QR area: white card with subtle shadow and centered QR image; below: copy secret and verify input inline.
- OTP inputs: single input that accepts 6 digits (auto-advance optional), accessible label "Authentication code".
- Error presentation: inline red text under the input + ephemeral toast for more severe states.
- Device remember: present as a subtle checkbox with info tooltip; opt for default off for security.

Design Philosophy:
- Keep UI calm and minimal, prioritizing clarity and step-by-step guidance to reduce user friction.
- Minimize cognitive load: show single action per step (scan, verify, backup).
- Provide clear remediation paths (use recovery code, contact support) for lost device cases.

---

Developer notes / Implementation priorities:
1. Implement backend TOTP flows and secure storage first (core security).
2. Add Twilio SMS sending with configurable env keys and mocked provider for staging.
3. Build endpoints for enable/disable/verify and test thoroughly with unit & integration tests.
4. Implement frontend Profile 2FA card and TOTP setup modal; integrate login verification UI.
5. Add recovery code generation and display/regenerate flow.
6. Implement rate limiting, device remember tokens, tenant require-2fa enforcement, and audit logging.
7. Conduct security review and penetration testing focused on brute-force, replay, and secret storage.

